Margaret Thatcher set the example of what a woman

could achieve in British society, but her critics say she did little else to help women along.
Mrs. Thatcher, who trained as a chemist before studying law, said she viewed herself as prime minister, not as a woman.
she once asked.
"The truth is that although Mrs. Thatcher is a woman, she doesn't believe in the advancement of women," Clare Short, a Labor Party lawmaker, said last month.
However, campaigners for women rights say there are encouraging signs at the grassroots.
But as prime minister, she angered feminists by often emphasizing women's traditional roles of homemakers and care-givers.
